### 4. The Evidence: Correlating Metrics to Real-World Outcomes

Engineering leadership will only adopt this tooling if the metrics map to business outcomes. You can correlate these specific vectors directly to established platform KPIs:

* **Time to First Successful Call (TTFSC) $\leftrightarrow$ Example Completeness & Validity.**
* *Evidence:* Developers rarely read schema descriptions top-to-bottom; they copy-paste the JSON payload or cURL snippet. If examples are missing or syntactically invalid, TTFSC spikes from minutes to hours. Validated examples are the strongest predictor of rapid onboarding.


* **Support Ticket Volume $\leftrightarrow$ Error Completeness & Consistency.**
* *Evidence:* When developers receive a generic `400 Bad Request` with an empty body, their only recourse is to open a support ticket. Standardized, documented error schemas allow developers to self-serve their fixes. High operational completeness correlates inversely with support load.


* **SDK Bug Rates & Production Incidents $\leftrightarrow$ Schema Precision.**
* *Evidence:* Auto-generated client libraries rely entirely on schema precision. If an API returns an unbounded array, or a string that is actually a UUID without declaring the `format: uuid`, generated clients will use incorrect native types, leading to runtime panics, out-of-memory errors, or integration breakages in strongly-typed languages. Precision acts as a client-side firewall.